# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deforestation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The **2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires** season saw a year-to-year surge in fires occurring in the Amazon rainforest and Amazon biome within Brazil, Bolivia, Paraguay, and Peru during that year's Amazonian tropical dry season.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Fires normally occur around the dry season as slash-and-burn methods are used to clear the forest to make way for agriculture, livestock, logging, and mining, leading to deforestation of the Amazon rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Such activity is generally illegal within these nations, but enforcement of environmental protection can be lax.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The increased rates of fire counts in 2019 led to international concern about the fate of the Amazon rainforest, which is the world's largest terrestrial carbon dioxide sink and plays a significant role in mitigating global warming.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] As of August 29, 2019, INPE reported more than 80,000 fires across all of Brazil, a 77% year-to-year increase for the same tracking period, with more than 40,000 in the Brazil's Legal Amazon (*Amazônia Legal* or BLA), which contains 60% of the Amazon.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Similar year-to-year increases in fires were subsequently reported in Bolivia, Paraguay and Peru, with the 2019 fire counts within each nation of over 19,000, 11,000 and 6,700, respectively, as of August 29, 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It is estimated that over 906 thousand hectares (2.24×10^6 acres; 9,060 km2; 3,500 mi2) of forest within the Amazon biome has been lost to fires in 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In addition to the impact on global climate, the fires created environmental concerns from the excess carbon dioxide (CO2) and carbon monoxide (CO) within the fires' emissions, potential impacts on the biodiversity of the Amazon, and threats to indigenous tribes that live within the forest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Ecologists estimated that the dieback from the Amazon rainforest due to the fires could cost Brazil US$957 billion to US$3.5 trillion over a 30-year period.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro initially remained ambivalent and rejected international calls to take action, asserting that the criticism was sensationalist.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Following increased pressure at the 45th G7 summit and a threat to reject the pending European Union–Mercosur free trade agreement, Bolsonaro dispatched over 44,000 Brazilian troops and allocated funds to fight the fires, and later signed a decree to prevent such fires for a sixty-day period.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Other Amazonian countries have been affected by the wildfires in higher or lesser degree.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The number of hectares of Bolivian rainforest affected by the wildfires were roughly equal to those of Brazil, being the area of Bolivia only about one-eighth of Brazil's.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolivian president Evo Morales was similarly blamed for past policies that encouraged deforestation, Morales has also taken proactive measures to fight the fires and seek aid from other countries.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] At the G7 summit, Macron negotiated with the other nations to allocate US$22 million for emergency aid to the Amazonian countries affected by the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] There are 670 million ha (1.7 billion acres; 6.7 million km2; 2.6 million mi2) of Amazon rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Human-driven deforestation of the Amazon rainforest has been a major concern for decades as the rainforest's impact on the global climate has been measured.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] From a global climate perspective, the Amazon has been the world's largest carbon dioxide sink, and estimated to capture up to 25% of global carbon dioxide generation into plants and other biomass.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Without this sink, atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations would increase and contribute towards higher global temperatures, thus making the viability of the Amazon a global concern.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Further, when the forest is lost through fire, additional carbon dioxide is released to the atmosphere, and could potentially contribute significantly to the total carbon dioxide content.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The flora also generates significant quantities of water vapor through transpiration which travel large distances to other parts of South America via atmospheric rivers and contribute to the precipitation in these areas.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Human-driven deforestation of the Amazon is used to clear land for agriculture, livestock, and mining, and for its lumber.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Fires are most common in July through August.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In some cases, workers performing the burn are unskilled, and may inadvertently allow these fires to spread.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While most countries in the Amazon do have laws and environmental enforcement against deforestation, these are not well enforced, and much of the slash-and-burn activity is done illegally.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Deforestation leads to a large number of observed fires across the Amazon during the dry season, usually tracked by satellite data.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While it is possible for naturally occurring wildfires to occur in the Amazon, the chances are far less likely to occur, compared to those in California or in Australia.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Even with global warming, spontaneous fires in the Amazon cannot come from warm weather alone, but warm weather is capable of exacerbating the fires once started as there will be drier biomass available for the fire to spread.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Alberto Setzer of INPE estimated that 99% of the wildfires in the Amazon basin are a result of human actions, either on purpose or accidentally.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Man-made fires in the Amazon also tend to elevate their smoke into the higher atmosphere due to the more intense burn of the dry biomass, compared with naturally occurring wildfires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Further evidence of the fires being caused by human activity is due to their clustering near roads and existing agricultural areas rather than remote parts of the forest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On November 18, 2019, Brazilian authorities announced the official deforestation figures, based on the PRODES satellite monitoring system for the 2019 forest year—from August 1, 2018, to July 31, 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The rate of deforestation was the "worst in more than a decade" with 970,000 hectares (2,400,000 acres) lost.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In August 2020 Brazil's National Institute for Space Research reported that satellite data shows that the number of fires in the Amazon increased by 28% to ~6,800 fires in July compared to the ~5,300 wildfires in July 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] This indicated a, potentially worsened, repeat of 2019's accelerated destruction of one of the world's largest protectable buffers against global warming in 2020.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Amazon fires can be separated into three broad categories.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] First, deforestation-related fires are those used to prepare the area for agriculture after a primary forest being felled and the vegetation left to dry.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Second, there are those agricultural burns, when fires are used to clear existing pastureland and/or by smallholders and traditional people in rotational agriculture.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Finally, the previous fire types can escape beyond intended limits and invade standing forests.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] When a forest burns for the first time, fire intensity is usually low and flames are mostly restricted to the understory while repeated fire events have higher intensity.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Forest fires are a threat to the Amazonian biodiversity and jeopardize the ability of forest trees to mitigate climate change by storing carbon.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] When studying Amazonian fires, it is important to consider the marked spatial differences in precipitation patterns across the Amazon Basin, which does not have a single dry season.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil's role in deforestation of the Amazon rainforest has been a significant issue during the 1930s, as 60% of the Amazon is contained within Brazil, designated as the Brazil's Legal Amazon (*Amazônia Legal*, BLA).
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Since the 1970s, Brazil has consumed approximately 12 percent of the forest, representing roughly 77.7 million ha (192 million acres)—an area larger than that of the US state of Texas.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Most of the deforestation has been for natural resources for the logging industry and land clearing for agricultural and mining use.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Forest removal to make way for cattle ranching was the leading cause of deforestation in the Brazilian Amazon from the mid-1960s on.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Amazon region has become the largest cattle ranching territory in the world.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According to the World Bank, some 80% of deforested land is used for cattle ranching.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Seventy percent of formerly forested land in the Amazon, and 91% of land deforested since 1970, is used for livestock pasture.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Deforestation within Brazil is partially driven by growing demand for beef and soy exports, particularly to China and Hong Kong.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In the first seven months of 2019, soy exports to China rose by 18% due to trading tensions between the United States and China.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil is one of the largest exporters of beef, accounting for more than 20% of global trade of the commodity.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil exported over 1.6 million tonnes of beef in 2018, the highest volume in recorded history.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil's cattle herd has increased by 56% over the last two decades.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Ranchers wait until the dry season to slash-and-burn to give time for the cattle to graze.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Soybean production has increased from 75.32 million metric tons in 2010/11 to 118.8 million metric tons in 2018/19.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Amazon accounts for 14 million of the 284 million acres of soy plantations in Brazil.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While slash-and-burn can be controlled, unskilled farmers may end up causing wildfires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Wildfires have increased as the agricultural sector has pushed into the Amazon basin and spurred deforestation.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In recent years, "land-grabbers" (*grileiros*) have been illegally cutting deep into the forest in "Brazil's indigenous territories and other protected forests throughout the Amazon".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Past data from INPE has shown the number of fires with the BLA from January to August in any year to be routinely higher than 60,000 fires from 2002 to 2007 and as high as 90,000 in 2003.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Fire counts have generally been higher in years of drought (2007 and 2010), which are often coupled with El Niño events.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Within international attention on the protection of the Amazon around the early 2000s, Brazil took a more proactive approach to deforestation of the Amazon rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil also invested in more effective measures to fight fires, including fire-fighting airplanes in 2012.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By 2014, USAID was teaching the indigenous people how to fight fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] As a result of enforcement of PPCDAM, the rate of deforestation in the Brazilian Amazon dropped 83.5% of their 2004 rates by 2012.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, in 2014, Brazil fell into an economic crisis, and as part of that recovery, pushed heavily on its exports of beef and soy to help bolster its economy, which caused a reversal in the falling deforestation rates.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Brazilian government has been defunding scientific research since the economic crisis.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] To support PPCDAM, the INPE began developing systems to monitor the Amazon rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] One early effort was the Amazon Deforestation Satellite Monitoring Project (PRODES), which is a highly detailed satellite imagery-based approach to calculate wildfires and deforestation losses on an annual basis.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In 2015, INPE launched five complementary projects as part of the Terra Brasilis project to monitor deforestation closer to real-time.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Among these include the Real-Time Deforestation Detection System (DETER) satellite alert system, allowing them to capture incidents of wildfires in 15-day cycles.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The daily data is published on the regularly updated Brazilian Environmental Institute government website, and later corroborated with the annual and more accurate PRODES data.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By December 2017, INPE had completed a modernization process and had expanded its system to analyze and share data on forest fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It launched its new TerraMA2Q platform—software which adapts fire-monitoring data software including the "occurrence of irregular fires".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Although the INPE was able to provide regional fire data since 1998, the modernization increased access.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Agencies that monitor and fight fires include the Brazilian Federal Environment and Renewable Resources Agency (IBAMA), as well as state authorities.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The INPE receives its images daily from 10 foreign satellites, including the Terra and Aqua satellites—part of the NASA's Earth Observation System (EOS).
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Land-grabbers had used Bolsonaro's election to extend their activities into cutting in the land of the previously isolated Apurinã people in Amazonas where the "world's largest standing tracts of unbroken rainforest" are found.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Upon entering office, Bolsonaro cut US$23 million from Brazil's environmental enforcement agency, making it difficult for the agency to regulate deforestation efforts.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE alerted the Brazilian government to larger-than-normal growth in the number of fires through June to August 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The first four months of the year were wetter-than-average, discouraging slash-and-burn efforts.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, with the start of the dry season in May 2019, the number of wildfires jumped greatly.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Additionally, NOAA reported that, regionally, the temperatures in the January–July 2019 period were the second warmest year-to-date on record.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE reported a year-to-year increase of 88% in wildfire occurrences in June 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] There was further increase in the rate of deforestation in July 2019, with the INPE estimating that more than 1,345 square kilometres (519 mi2; 134,500 ha; 332,000 acres) of land had been deforested in the month and would be on track to surpass the area of Greater London by the end of the month.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The month of August 2019 saw a large growth in the number of observed wildfires according to INPE.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 11, Amazonas had declared a state of emergency.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The state of Acre entered into an environmental alert on August 16.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In early August, local farmers in the Amazonian state of Pará placed an ad in the local newspaper calling for a *queimada* or "Day of Fire" on August 10, 2019, organizing large scale slash-and-burn operations knowing that there was little chance of interference from the government.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Shortly after, there was an increase in the number of wildfires in the region.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE reported on August 20 that it had detected 39,194 fires in the Amazon rainforest since January.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] This represented a 77 percent increase in the number of fires from the same time period in 2018.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, the NASA-funded NGO Global Fire Emissions Database (GFED) shows 2018 as an unusually low fire year compared to historic data from 2004 to 2005 which are years showing nearly double the number of counted fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE had reported that at least 74,155 fires have been detected in all of Brazil, which represents an 84-percent increase from the same period in 2018.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NASA originally reported in mid-August that MODIS satellites reported average numbers of fires in the region compared with data from the past 15 years; the numbers were above average for the year in the states of Amazonas and Rondônia, but below average for Mato Grosso and Pará.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NASA later clarified that the data set they had evaluated previous was through August 16, 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 26, 2019, NASA included more recent MODIS imagery to confirm that the number of fires were higher than in previous years.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 29, 80,000 fires had broken out in Brazil which represents a 77% rise on the same period in 2018, according to BBC.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While INPE's data had been reported in international sources earlier, news of the wildfires were not a major news story until around August 20, 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On that day, the smoke plume from the fires in Rondônia and Amazonas caused the sky to darken at around 2 p.m. over São Paulo—which is almost 2,800 kilometres (1,700 miles) away from the Amazon basin on the eastern coast.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NASA and US National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) also published satellite imagery from the Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) on NASA's Terra satellite in alignment with INPE's own, that showed smoke plumes from the wildfires were visible from space.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE and NASA data, along with photographs of the ongoing fires and impacts, caught international attention and became a rising topic on social media, with several world leaders, celebrities, and athletes expressing their concerns.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According to *Vox*, of all the concurrent wildfires elsewhere in the world, the wildfires in the Amazon rainforest in Brazil were the most "alarming".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In the months prior to August 2019, Bolsonaro mocked international and environmental groups that felt his pro-business actions enabled deforestation.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] At one point in August 2019, Bolsonaro jokingly calling himself "Captain Chainsaw" while asserting that INPE's data was inaccurate.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] After INPE announced an 88% increase of wildfires in July 2019, Bolsonaro claimed "the numbers were fake" and fired Ricardo Magnus Osório Galvão, the INPE director.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro claimed Galvão was using the data to lead an "anti-Brazil campaign".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro had claimed that the fires had been deliberately started by environmental NGOs, although he provided no evidence to back up the accusation.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NGOs such as WWF Brasil, Greenpeace, and the Brazilian Institute for Environmental Protection countered Bolsonaro's claims.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro, on August 22, argued that Brazil did not have the resources to fight the fires, as the "Amazon is bigger than Europe, how will you fight criminal fires in such an area?".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Historically, Brazil has been guarded about international intervention into the BLA, as the country sees the forest as a critical part of Brazil's economy.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro and his government have continued to speak out against any international oversight of the situation.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro considered French President Emmanuel Macron's comments to have a "sensationalist tone" and accusing him of interfering in what he considers is a local problem.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Of Macron and German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Bolsonaro stated: "They still haven't realized that Brazil is under new direction.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro's foreign minister Ernesto Araújo has also condemned the international criticism of Bolsonaro's reaction to the wildfires, calling it "savage and unfair" treatment towards Bolsonaro and Brazil.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Araújo stated that: "President Bolsonaro's government is rebuilding Brazil", and that foreign nations were using the "environmental crisis" as a weapon to stop this rebuilding.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] General Eduardo Villas Bôas, former commander of the Brazilian Army, considered the criticism of world leaders, like Macron and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, to be directly challenging "Brazilian sovereignty", and may need to be met with military response.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] With increased pressure from the international community, Bolsonaro appeared more willing to take proactive steps against the fires, saying by August 23, 2019, that his government would take a "zero tolerance" approach to environmental crimes.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] He engaged the Brazilian military to help fight the wildfires on August 24, which Joint Staff member Lt.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Raul Botelho stated was to create a "positive perception" of the government's efforts.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Among military support included 43,000 troops as well as four firefighting aircraft, and an allocated US$15.7 million for fire-fighting operations.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Initial efforts were principally located in the state of Rondônia, but the Defense Ministry stated they plan to offer support for all seven states affected by the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 28, Bolsonaro signed a decree banning the setting of fires in Brazil for a period of 60 days, making exceptions for those fires made purposely to maintain environmental forest health, to combat wildfires, and by the indigenous people of Brazil.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, as most fires are set illegally, it is unclear what impact this decree could have.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Rodrigo Maia, president of the Chamber of Deputies, announced that he would form a parliatary committee to monitor the problem.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In addition, he said that the Chamber will hold a general commission in the following days to assess the situation and propose solutions to the government.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] After a report from Globo Rural reveal that a WhatsApp group of 70 people was involved with the *Day of Fire*, Jair Bolsonaro determined the opening of investigations by Federal Police.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In a webcast issued November 28, 2019, President Jair Bolsonaro blamed actor and environmentalist Leonardo DiCaprio for the rainforest wildfires, alleging NGOs set the fires in return for donations.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] DiCaprio, Global Wildlife Conservation, and IUCN Species Survival Commission condemn Bolsonaro's accusations.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil banned clearing land by setting fire to it on 29 August 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In regards to the displacement of the indigenous people, Amnesty International has highlighted the change in protection of lands belonging to the indigenous people, and have called on other nations to pressure Brazil to restore these rights, as they are also essential to protecting the rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Ivaneide Bandeira Cardoso, founder of Kanindé, a Porto Velho-based advocacy group for indigenous communities, said Bolsonaro is directly responsible for the escalation of forest fires throughout the Amazon this year.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Cardoso said the wildfires are a "tragedy that affects all of humanity" since the Amazon plays an important role in the global ecosystem as a carbon sink to reduce the effects of climate change.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Thousands of Brazilian citizens held protests in several major cities from August 24, 2019, onward to challenge the government's reaction to the wildfires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Protesters around the world also held events at Brazilian embassies, including in London, Paris, Mexico City, and Geneva.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In addition to environmental harm, the slash-and-burn actions leading to the wildfires have threatened the approximately 306,000 indigenous people in Brazil who reside near or within the rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro had spoken out against the need to respect the demarcation of lands for indigenous people established in the 1988 Constitution of Brazil.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Additionally, some indigenous groups that have traditionally used fire management practices for agricultural livelihoods are being criminalized.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Some of these tribes have vowed to fight back against those engaged in deforestation to protect their lands.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Kerexu Yxapyry, a leader from Santa Catarina's Kerexu tribe, describes this conflict as, "We know our struggle will be arduous.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Maybe many of our leaders will be killed, but we are organized.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] International leaders and environmental NGOs have condemned President Bolsonaro for the extent of the wildfires within the Brazilian portion of the Amazon.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Several international governments and environmental groups raised concerns at Bolsonaro's stance on the rainforest and the lack of attempts by his government to slow the wildfires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Among the most vocal was Macron, given the proximity of French Guiana to Brazil.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Macron called the Amazon wildfires an "international crisis", while claiming the rainforest produces "20% of the world's oxygen"—a statement disputed by academics.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Discussion about the fires came into the final negotiations of the EU–Mercosur Free Trade Agreement between the EU and Mercosur, a trade bloc of Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, and Paraguay.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] With the wildfires on-going, both Macron and Irish Prime Minister Leo Varadkar have stated they will refuse to ratify the trade deal unless Brazil commits to protecting the environment.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, they have both been accused of using the fires as a pretext to scuttle an agreement that they already opposed on protectionist grounds.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Finance minister of Finland Mika Lintilä suggested the idea of an EU ban on Brazilian beef imports until the country takes steps to stop the deforestation.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Secretary-General of the Rainforest Foundation Norway (RFN), Øyvind Eggen, said that neither the "official deforestation figures" published by Brazilian authorities on November 18, 2019, nor the number of wildfires in Amazon in 2019, were normal.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On September 10, 2019, the US House Foreign Affairs Committee held a hearing in Washington, DC entitled "Preserving the Amazon: A Shared Moral Imperative".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In Bolivia, *chaqueo* is an annual seasonal agricultural practice and commonly relies on the controlled use of fire.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It was first authorized in 2001 during the government of Hugo Banzer Suarez.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolivia has 7.7 percent of the Amazon rainforest within its borders.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Bolivian Amazon covers 19.402 million hectares (47.94 million acres) which comprise 37.7 percent of Bolivia's forests and 17.7 percent of Bolivia's land mass.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolivia's forests cover a total of 51.407 million hectares (127.03 million acres), including the Chiquitano dry forests which is part of the Amazon biome and a transition zone between the Amazon rainforest and the drier forests of the southern Chaco region.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By September 14, 2019, Bolivia—which is one-eighth the size of Brazil—lost nearly 6 million acres (2.4 million hectares) of "forest and savanna".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The fires destroyed about the same area of rainforest than in Brazil.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 16, Bolivia's Santa Cruz had declared a departmental emergency because of the forest fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] From August 18 to August 23, approximately 800 thousand hectares (2.0 million acres) of the Chiquitano dry forests were destroyed, more than what was lost over a typical two-year period.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 24, the fires had already affected 1,011 thousand hectares (2.50 million acres) of forestland in the Santa Cruz and were burning near Santa Cruz, Bolivia.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 26, wildfires had reached over 728 thousand hectares (1.80 million acres) of Bolivia's savanna and tropical forests, according to the Bolivian Information Agency (BIA).
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Over a period of five days, from August 18 to August 22, 450 thousand hectares (1.1 million acres) of forest near Roboré were burned.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 25, 4,000 state employees and volunteers were fighting the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Throughout August, wildfires have been spreading across four states. [By August 26, fires in the Dionisio Foianini Triangle—the Brazil-Bolivia-Paraguay triangle had reached savannah and tropical forest "near Bolivia's border with Paraguay and Brazil".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Bolivian government intervened after it was clear that the fires had surpassed local and regional response capabilities.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In the week of August 18, Morales dispatched soldiers and three helicopters to fight fires in an area about the size of Oregon.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 22, Morales contracted the Colorado-based Boeing 747 Supertanker (also known as Global SuperTanker) to conduct firefighting missions over the Bolivian Amazon.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The 747 Supertanker is the largest firefighting aircraft in the world, which can hold approximately 19,000 gallons of water per trip.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Morales has stated that the governments of many countries including Spain, Chile, Perú, France, the EU, among others have reached out to him to provide help for fighting the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The government had been trying to determine the cause of the fires, with the Bolivian land management authority attributing 87% of the fires present in areas without authorization.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Multiple NGOs assert that deforestation rates in Bolivia increased 200 percent after the government quadrupled available land for deforestation to small farmers in 2015.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Political opponents of Morales alleged that the Supreme Decree 3973 Archived August 25, 2019, at the Wayback Machine, a mandate to further beef production in the Amazon region, is a major cause of the Bolivian fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, this Supreme Decree only extends the authorized but regulated use of fire already legal in Santa Cruz to the Beni Department, where forest fire issues are not a significant issue.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By September 9, total forests that had been affected by fires in Bolivia was estimated as 1,700 thousand hectares (4.2 million acres), more than double from estimates two weeks prior, but far less extended than the forest fires that occurred in 2004 and 2010.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 22, fire emergencies in Paraguay's Alto Paraguay district and the UNESCO protected Pantanal region were issued by its federal government.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Paraguay President Mario Abdo Benítez was in close contact with Bolivia's Morales to coordinate response efforts.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 17, as wind direction changed, flames from fires in Bolivia began to enter northern Paraguay's Three Giants natural reserve in the Paraguayan Pantanal natural region.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 24, when the situation had stabilized, Paraguay had lost 39,000 hectares (96,000 acres) in the Pantanal.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] An Universidad Nacional de Asunción representative lamented the disaster failed to attract as much media attention as the fires in the Amazon rainforest.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While most of the Pantanal regions—140,000 and 195,000 square kilometres (54,000 and 75,000 sq mi)—is within Brazil's borders in the state of Mato Grosso do Sul, the natural region also extends into Mato Grosso and portions of Bolivia.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It sprawls over an area estimated at between 140,000 and 195,000 square kilometres (54,000 and 75,000 sq mi).
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Within the Pantanal natural region, which is located between Brazil and Bolivia, is the "world's largest tropical wetland area".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According one of the engineers charged with monitoring satellite data showing the "evolution of the fires", the Pantanal is a "complex, fragile, and high-risk ecosystem because it's being transformed from a wetland to a productive system".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Pantana is bounded by the Humid Chaco to the south, the Arid Chaco dry forests to the southwest, Cerrado savannas lie to the north, east and southeast, and the Chiquitano dry forests, to the west and northwest, where thousands of hectares burned in Bolivia.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] A national parks researcher said that outsiders only know the Amazon, which is a "shame because the Pantanal is a very important ecological place".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Paraná River, which flows through Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay, is the "second largest river system in South America".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Peru had nearly twice the growth in the number of fires in 2019 than Brazil, with most believed to be illegally set by ranchers, miners, and coca growers.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Much of the fires are in the Madre de Dios which borders Brazil and Bolivia, though the fires there are not a result of those started in the other countries, according to the regional authority.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, they are still concerned about the impact of downwind emissions, particularly carbon monoxide, on residents of Madre de Dios.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] There were 128 forest fires reported in Peru in August 2019.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 22, NASA's AIRS published maps of increased carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide resulting from Brazil's wildfires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On the same day, the European Union's Copernicus Climate Change Service reported a "discernible spike" in emissions of carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide generated by the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Areas downwind of the fires have become covered with smoke, which can potentially last upwards of months at a time if the fires are left to burn out.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Hospitals in cities like Porto Velho had reported over three times the average number of cases of patients affected by smoke over the same year-to-year period in August 2019 than in other previous years.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Besides hindering breathing, the smoke can exacerbates patients with asthma or bronchitis and have potential cancer risk, generally affecting the youth and elderly the most.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According to the World Wildlife Fund, the jaguar, for example, is already "near threatened" and the loss of food supplies and habitat due to the fires make the situation more critical.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Scientists at the Natural History Museum in London described how while some forests have adapted to fire as "important part of a forest ecosystem's natural cycle", the Amazon rainforest—which is "made up of lowland, wetland forests"—is "not well-equipped to deal with fire".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Other Amazon basin ecosystems, like the Cerrado region, with its "large savannah, and lots of plants there have thick, corky, fire-resistant stems", is "fire-adapted".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Mazeika Sullivan, associate professor at Ohio State University's School of Environment and Natural Resources, explained that the fires could have a massive toll on wildlife in the short term as many animals in the Amazon are not adapted for extraordinary fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Sloths, lizards, anteaters, and frogs may unfortunately perish in larger numbers than others due to their small size and lack of mobility.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Endemic species, like Milton's titi and Mura's saddleback tamarin, are believed to be beset by the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Aquatic species could also be affected due to the fires changing the water chemistry into a state unsuitable for life.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Long-term effects could be more catastrophic.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Parts of the Amazon rainforest's dense canopy were destroyed by the fires, therefore, exposing the lower levels of the ecosystem, which then alters the energy flow of the food chain.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The fires affect water chemistry (such as decreasing the amount of dissolved oxygen in the water), temperature, and erosion rates, which in turn affects fish and mammals that depend on fish, such as the giant otter.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 22, the Bishops Conference for Latin America called the fires a "tragedy" and urged the UN, the international community, and governments of Amazonian countries, to "take serious measures to save the world's lungs".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Colombian President Ivan Duque stated he wanted to lead a conservation pact with the other nations that share the Amazon rainforest with plans to present this to the UN General Assembly.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Attention to the wildfires increased in the week prior to the G7 summit discussions on August 24–26 in Biarritz, France, led by President Macron.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Macron stated his intent to open discussions related to the wildfires in the Brazilian part of the Amazon and Bolsonaro's response to them.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro expressed concern to United States president Donald Trump, that with Brazil not part of the G7, the country would be unrepresented in any such debate.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Trump offered to take the position of the Brazilian government to the meeting and said that the US government did not agree to discuss the issue without Brazil's presence.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Trump himself was absent from the environmental portion of the summit held on August 26, 2019, that discussed the fires and climate change, though members of his advisory team were in attendance.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] During the summit, Macron and Chilean president Sebastián Piñera negotiated with the other nations to authorize US$22 million in emergency funding to Amazonian countries to help fight the fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Trump administration did not approve of the measure as the funding set certain requirements on its use.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] When the final negotiations were completed, Bolsonaro stated that he would refuse those funds for Brazil, claiming that Macron's interests were about protecting France's agricultural business in French Guiana from Brazil's competition.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro also criticised Macron by comparing the Amazon fires to the Notre-Dame de Paris fire earlier in 2019, suggesting Macron should take care of their internal fires before reaching out internationally.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The governors of the states of Brazil most affected by the fires pressured Bolsonaro to accept the aid given.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro later clarified that he would accept foreign aid for the fires, but only if Brazil has the authority to determine how it is used.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil's Bolsonaro stated on August 28, 2019, that the countries sharing the Amazon rainforest, excluding Venezuela, will hold a summit in Colombia on September 6, 2019, to discuss the ongoing Amazon fire situation.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Representatives from seven countries attended: Brazil, Colombia, Peru, Ecuador, Bolivia, Guyana and Suriname.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The countries signed a pact to coordinate monitoring of the Amazon forest and disaster response, and a better information network to coordinate their responses.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The pact will also seek cooperative efforts to reduce the need for illegal deforestation in their countries.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The media coverage had also broadly overshadowed the Amazon fires in Bolivia, Peru, and Paraguay by the fires and international impact of those in the BLA.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Amazon wildfires also occurred shortly after major wildfires reported in Greenland and Siberia after a globally hotter-than-average June and July, drawing away coverage of these natural disasters.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Some of these photographs shared on social media were from past fire events in the Amazon or from fires elsewhere.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Agence France-Presse and *El Comercio* published guides to help people "fact-check" on misleading photos.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] American actor Leonardo DiCaprio said his environmental organization Earth Alliance is donating $5 million to local groups and indigenous communities to help protect the Amazon.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In a webcast on November 28, 2019, President Jair Bolsonaro said DiCaprio's donations encourage NGOs to set the fires in return for donations, a charge DiCaprio, Global Wildlife Conservation, and IUCN Species Survival Commission vehemently denied.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Instagram has been a platform for many celebrities who have spoken out about the wildfires such as Cara Delevingne, who posted a picture of the wildfires with the caption "#PrayForAmazonia".
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Other celebrities who made public contributions include actresses Vanessa Hudgens and Lana Condor, and Japanese musician Yoshiki.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 26, 2019, Europe's richest man, Bernard Arnault, declared that his LVMH group will donate $11 million to aid in the fight against the Amazon rainforest wildfires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] American restaurateur Eddie Huang said he is going vegan as a result of the 2019 Amazon fires.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Khloé Kardashian urged her 98 million Instagram followers to adopt a plant-based diet for the same reason.
[src:deforestation/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] 2021 single "Amazonia" by French metal band Gojira and its music video are a response the fires.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference**, more commonly referred to as **COP26**, was the 26th United Nations Climate Change conference, held at the SEC Centre in Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom, from 31 October to 13 November 2021.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The president of the conference was UK cabinet minister Alok Sharma.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The result of COP26 was the Glasgow Climate Pact, negotiated through consensus of the representatives of the 197 attending parties.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Owing to late interventions from India and China that weakened a move to end coal power and fossil fuel subsidies, the conference ended with the adoption of a less stringent resolution than some anticipated.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nevertheless, the pact was the first climate deal to explicitly commit to reducing the use of coal.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It included wording that encouraged more urgent greenhouse gas emissions cuts and promised more climate finance for developing countries to adapt to climate impacts.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the midst of the conference, on 6 November 2021, a march against inadequate action at the conference, as well as for other climate change-related issues, became the largest protest in Glasgow since anti-Iraq War marches in 2003.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Additional rallies took place in 100 other countries.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United Kingdom holds the presidency of COP26 until the start of COP27.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Initially, the Minister of State for Energy and Clean Growth, Claire Perry, was appointed as president of the conference, but she was removed on 31 January 2020, several months after she had stepped down as an MP.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Former Prime Minister David Cameron and former Foreign Secretary William Hague declined to take the role.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 February 2020, Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Secretary Alok Sharma was appointed.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 8 January 2021, Sharma was succeeded by Kwasi Kwarteng as Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Secretary and moved to the Cabinet Office, in order to focus on the presidency full-time.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nigel Topping, the former CEO of climate change action organization We Mean Business, was appointed the UK Government's High Level Climate Action Champion for COP26.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Italy partnered with the UK in leading COP26.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] For the most part, their role was in preparatory work such as the hosting of a pre-COP session and an event for young people called Youth4Climate 2020: Driving Ambition.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] These events took place between 28 September and 2 October 2020 in Milan.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic, in April 2020 the conference was postponed to 31 October – 12 November 2021.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Both host countries, Italy and the UK, were heavily affected by the pandemic, and the venue of the conference, the SEC Centre in Glasgow, was converted in May 2020 into a temporary hospital for COVID-19 patients in Scotland.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Earlier in 2021, the UK and Italy hosted summits of the G7 and G20, respectively.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Independent observers noted that though not directly related, the postponement gave the international community time to respond to the outcome of the United States presidential election, held in November 2020.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] President Donald Trump had withdrawn the United States from the Paris Agreement, although this could not take effect until the day after the election; while his Democratic challengers pledged to immediately rejoin and increase ambition to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Joe Biden did so upon being elected as president.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] At the conference, Biden apologized for Trump's withdrawal from the agreement.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previous summits have been sponsored by fossil fuel companies.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] To reduce this influence, the UK government decided that sponsors "have to have real commitments in place to help them reach net zero in the near future".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The first principal partners included three British energy companies and a banking and insurance company.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Before the summit councils in and around Glasgow pledged to plant 18 million trees during the following decade: the Clyde Climate Forest (CCF) is projected to increase tree coverage in the urban areas of the Greater Glasgow region to 20%.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In September 2021, the conference was urged by Climate Action Network to ensure attendees would be able to attend in spite of travel restrictions related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the months before the conference, the British government had restrictions on travel from certain countries in place, and COVID passports were required in certain venues.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Critics suggested unequal deployment of COVID-19 vaccines worldwide could exclude the participation of representatives of poorer countries most affected by climate change.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UK subsequently relaxed travel rules for delegations.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Only four Pacific Islands nations sent delegations due to COVID-19 travel restrictions, with most island nations compelled to send smaller teams than they otherwise would have.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Organizers have in place numerous COVID-19 rules for attendees, dependent on vaccination status.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 4 June 2021, a nighttime light projection onto the Tolbooth Steeple was installed, under the Climate Clock initiative.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The projected Deadline and Lifeline statistics count the time window before 1.5 °C warming would become inevitable, and the percentage of global energy delivered through renewables, respectively.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Scottish Events Campus (SEC), known as the Blue Zone, temporarily became United Nations territory: the other main venue is the Green Zone at Glasgow Science Centre.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The summit was described as receiving "the cleanest electricity in the UK", as 70% was supplied from low-carbon nuclear power from plants in Torness and Hunterston B, while the rest mostly came from wind power.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The provision of medical services for the event was provided by BASICS Scotland, Amvale Medical and the Scottish Ambulance Service.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The medical centre was visited by both Scottish National Clinical Director Jason Leitch and Scottish Health Secretary Humza Yousaf during the conference.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Twenty-five thousand delegates from nearly 200 countries were expected to attend, and around 120 heads of state came.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Australian prime minister Scott Morrison spoke.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Czech prime minister Andrej Babiš denounced the proposed European Union Fit for 55 laws, part of the European Green Deal, saying that the bloc "can achieve nothing without the participation of the largest polluters such as China or the USA".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Prince Charles addressed the opening ceremony in person.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Queen Elizabeth, having been advised to rest by doctors, addressed the conference by video message.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Bill Gates called for a "green industrial revolution" to beat the climate crisis.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fossil fuel industry was the largest delegation at the conference, with 503 people accredited.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In October 2021, China's leader Xi Jinping announced he would not be attending the conference in person and instead delivered a written address as the organizers did not provide an opportunity for a video address.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] With greenhouse gas emissions by China being the world's largest, Reuters said this made it less likely the conference would result in a significant climate deal.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, a Chinese delegation led by climate change envoy Xie Zhenhua did attend.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The 2021 global energy crisis intensified pressures on China ahead of the summit.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The prime ministers or heads of state of South Africa, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Mexico, Brazil, Turkey, Malaysia and Vatican City also did not attend the meeting.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russian president Vladimir Putin said his non-attendance was due to concerns relating to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Iranian president Ebrahim Raisi did not attend; a formal request had been made by Struan Stevenson and Iranian exiles of the National Council of Resistance of Iran to the Scotland police, to arrest Raisi for crimes against humanity if he attended based on the legal concept of universal jurisdiction.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Saudi crown prince Mohammed bin Salman also did not attend the summit.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Brazilian president Jair Bolsonaro, who faced international condemnation over rising deforestation of the Amazon rainforest, also decided not to attend the summit personally.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The non-attendance of both Putin and Xi received criticism from U.S. president Joe Biden and former American president Barack Obama.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Myanmar and Afghanistan were entirely absent; both countries had their UN-recognized governments ousted militarily in 2021.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Myanmar military junta was blocked from entry to the summit.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Six exiled Afghan climate experts had their applications rejected by the UNFCCC.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Additionally, the island nation of Kiribati did not send participants, while fellow island nations Vanuatu and Samoa registered but did not send a delegation.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Under the Paris Agreement, countries submitted pledges called nationally determined contributions, to limit their greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Under the framework of the Paris Agreement, each country is expected to submit enhanced nationally determined contributions every five years, to ratchet up the ambition to mitigate climate change.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] When the Paris Agreement was signed at COP21, the conference of 2020 was set to be the first ratcheting up.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Even though the 2020 conference was postponed to 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, dozens of countries still had not updated their pledges by early October 2021.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Collective progress towards implementation of the Paris Agreement in mitigation, adaptation and finance flows and means of implementation and support will be measured by global stocktakes, the first of which is due to be completed in 2023.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 November 2021, the participating 197 countries agreed to a new deal, known as the Glasgow Climate Pact, aimed at staving off dangerous climate change.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The final agreement explicitly mentions coal, which is the single biggest contributor to climate change.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previous COP agreements have not mentioned coal, oil or gas, or even fossil fuels in general, as a driver, or major cause of climate change, making the Glasgow Climate Pact the first ever climate deal to explicitly plan to reduce unabated coal power.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The wording in the agreement refers to an intention to "phase down" use of unabated coal power, rather than to phase it out.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] From this wording it implicitly follows that utilizing coal power with "abation" (net-zero emission), e.g. by neutralizing the resulting carbon dioxide via the CO2-to-stone process, need not be reduced.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, this carbon capture and storage is too expensive for most coal fired power stations.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Over 140 countries pledged to reach net-zero emissions.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 100 countries, including Brazil, pledged to reverse deforestation by 2030.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The final text of the Glasgow Climate Pact include a call to: "accelerating efforts towards... phase-out of inefficient fossil fuel subsidies".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 40 countries pledged to move away from coal.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United States and China reached an agreement about cooperation on measures to stop climate change, including lowering methane emissions, phasing out the use of coal, and forest conservation.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] 39 countries and institutions signed the Glasgow Statement, an international agreement to shift international public finance away from fossil fuels towards clean energy.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] If implemented properly, the Glasgow Statement will shift $28 billion per year from fossil fuels to clean energy.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India promised to draw half of its energy requirement from renewable sources by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2070.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers such as GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover, and Mercedes-Benz have committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Major car manufacturing nations like China, the US, Japan, Germany, and South Korea, as well as Toyota, Volkswagen, Nissan-Renault-Mitsubishi, Stellantis, Honda, and Hyundai had not signed up to the pledge.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] New pledges for financial help for climate change mitigation and adaptation were announced.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Climate Action Tracker on 9 November 2021, described the results as follows: the global temperature will rise by 2.7 °C by the end of the century with current policies.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if only the pledges for 2030 are implemented, by 2.1 °C if the long-term targets are also achieved and by 1.8 °C if all the announced targets are fully achieved.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Glasgow Financial Alliance for Net Zero (GFANZ) announced that financial institutions controlling $130 trillion were now signed up to 'net zero' emissions pledges by 2050.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The world leaders' summit was on 1 and 2 November, with each leader giving a national statement.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An important goal of the conference organizers is to keep a 1.5 °C (2.7 °F) temperature rise within reach.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the BBC, negotiators who may be key to the dealmaking include Xie Zhenhua, Ayman Shasly, Sheikh Hasina and Teresa Ribera.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China said it aims to peak CO2 emissions before 2030 and to become carbon neutral by 2060.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It was asked to set a clear earlier date as this would have a very large "positive impact" on the Paris Agreement targets.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Officials later said the 2030 target was something to "strive to" and not something to be ensured.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Signatories of the 2014 agreement, the New York Declaration on Forests, pledged to half deforestation by 2020 and end it by 2030; however, in the 2014–2020 period deforestation increased.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Indonesia's environment minister Siti Nurbaya Bakar stated that "forcing Indonesia to zero deforestation in 2030 is clearly inappropriate and unfair".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Article 6 of the Paris Agreement, which describes rules for an international carbon market (such as for trees in the deforestation agreement) and other forms of international cooperation, is being discussed as it is the last piece of the rulebook remaining to be finalized.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Although the parties have agreed in principle to avoid double counting of emission reduction across more than one country's greenhouse gas inventory, exactly how much double counting will actually occur remains unclear.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Carrying forward pre-2020 Kyoto carbon credits will be discussed, but is highly unlikely to be agreed.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Therefore, Article 6 rules could make a big difference to future emissions.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Climate finance for adaptation and mitigation was one of the principal topics of negotiation.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Poor countries want more money for adaptation, whereas donors prefer to finance mitigation as that has a chance of making a profit.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Appointed to the role of Climate Finance Adviser was Mark Carney, former Governor of the Bank of England.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Paris agreement included US$100 billion annually in finance by 2020 for developing countries.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, wealthy countries failed to live up to that promise, with members of the OECD behind in their commitments and unlikely to reach the agreed amount before 2023.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A group of large finance companies committed to net zero portfolios and loan books by 2050.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Scotland became the first country to contribute to a loss and damage fund.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] South Africa is set to receive $8.5 billion to end its reliance on coal, details are sparse regarding capping mines, exports and local community support for the workers in the industry.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Countries including Chile, Poland, Ukraine, South Korea, Indonesia and Vietnam also agreed to phase out coal in the 2030s for major economies, and the 2040s for poorer nations.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] These nations include some of the world's most intensive users of coal.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, they do not include the world's largest users of the fuel, China, India, and the United States of America.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Japan is to invest $100 million in the transformation of fossil-fired plants into ones based on ammonia and hydrogen fuel.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The US and many other countries agreed to limit methane emissions.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 80 countries signed up to a global methane pledge, agreeing to cut emissions by 30% by the end of the decade.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The US and European leaders say tackling the potent greenhouse gas is crucial to keeping warming limited to 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Australia, China, Russia, India and Iran did not sign the deal, but it is hoped more countries will join later.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia demanded sanction relief on green investment projects for energy companies such as Gazprom.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia's climate envoy Ruslan Edelgeriyev accused Western countries of hypocrisy for urging Russia "to reduce methane leakages and yet we have Gazprom under sanctions".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Many attendees committed to net-zero carbon emissions, with India and Japan making specific commitments at the conference.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India, the third-largest emitter of carbon dioxide by jurisdiction, set the latest target date planning to be net-zero by 2070.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Japan is to offer up to $10 billion in additional funding to support decarbonization in Asia.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Earlier in October, China—the largest emitter of carbon dioxide by jurisdiction—had committed to net-zero carbon emissions by 2060, and it was believed by the British government that India would issue a similar commitment.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, this was the first time that a date for carbon neutrality had been given as part of India's climate policy.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Green hydrogen has emerged as one of the major areas where companies can collaborate to help decarbonize hard to abate industries.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Big city mayors concerned about climate—the C40 Cities Climate Leadership Group—such as Istanbul Mayor Ekrem İmamoğlu, called for more urban climate adaptation, especially in low-income countries.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] 45 countries, including the UK, U.S., Japan, Germany, India, Indonesia, Morocco, Vietnam, Philippines, Gabon, Ethiopia, Ghana and Uruguay, pledged to give more than $4 billion for transition to sustainable agriculture.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A draft text published on 10 November asked governments to accelerate phase-outs and desubsidization of fossil fuels, the largest source of (anthropogenic) global greenhouse gas emissions, but was opposed by several countries with large fossil fuels based economic sectors.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Business leaders and politicians including Jeff Bezos, Prince Charles, Boris Johnson, Joe Biden and Angela Merkel who travelled to Glasgow in private airplanes were accused of hypocrisy by commentators and campaigners.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Event planners, however, insisted that the conference would be carbon-neutral.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Around 400 private jets arrived at Glasgow for the talks.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In October 2021, the BBC reported that a huge leak of documents revealed that Saudi Arabia, Japan and Australia were among countries asking the UN to play down the need to move rapidly away from fossil fuels.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It also showed that some wealthy nations (including Switzerland and Australia) were questioning paying more to poorer states to move to greener technologies.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The BBC reported that the lobbying raised questions for the COP26 climate summit.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Australian government has been criticized for hosting a fossil fuel company at the summit, not enhancing its ambitions closer to its capacities, not pledging to reduce methane emissions and not pledging to phase out coal.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In an interview shortly before the conference, Greta Thunberg, asked how optimistic she was that the conference could achieve anything, responded "Nothing has changed from previous years really.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The leaders will say 'we'll do this and we'll do this, and we will put our forces together and achieve this', and then they will do nothing.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Maybe some symbolic things and creative accounting and things that don't really have a big impact.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] By 1 November, at the outset of the conference, the climate change activist Greta Thunberg criticized the summit at a protest in Glasgow with members from the organization Fridays for Future, saying "This COP26 is so far just like the previous COPs and that has led us nowhere.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 5 November, a Fridays for Future protest at which Thunberg spoke gathered thousands of people, largely schoolchildren.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Attendees supported more immediate and far-reaching action on climate change.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Glasgow City Council and most neighbouring councils stated that students would not be punished if parents informed their schools of the absence.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 6 November—the Global Day of Action for Climate Justice—around 100,000 people joined a march in Glasgow, according to BBC News, with coaches and group cycle rides organized for participants to travel from around the United Kingdom.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The protests were the largest in Glasgow since anti-Iraq War marches in 2003.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A London march drew 10,000 people according to police and 20,000 according to organizers.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] *The Times* anticipated that total participants would number over two million.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An additional 100 marches took place elsewhere in the country, with a total of 300 protests across 100 countries, according to *The Guardian*.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 8 November, Fridays for Future activists including Dominika Lasota and Nicole Becker held a protest prior to a speech by former US president Barack Obama, arguing that he had failed to fulfill his promise to provide US$100 billion in climate funding to developing countries.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The protestors held banners stating, "Show us the money".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Vanessa Nakate and indigenous activists gave speeches at Glasgow.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Issues highlighted by protesters included putting corporate interests at the forefront and politicians' failure to address the climate emergency with the required urgency as well as its underlying causes.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kahnawake Mohawk people, ecology scientists, vegan activists, trade unionists and socialists were present at marches.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] One intended participant, the Israeli energy minister Karine Elharrar, was unable to attend on 1 November due to wheelchair accessibility issues.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The sustainability of the COP26 menu was criticized by the animal and climate justice group Animal Rebellion, with almost 60% of the menu being meat and dairy based, and dishes labelled as high-carbon being served at food stands.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The head of catering at COP26, Lorna Wilson, said that staff had been "working towards" a catering strategy of 95% food from the UK and 5% from abroad.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Wilson said the menu was 40% plant-based and 60% vegetarian overall.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The event eliminated single-use cups and plastics.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There was concern about the inclusion and influence of large delegations of industries, particularly big polluting companies, and financial organizations involved in the causes of greenhouse gas emissions at the conference.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Further criticisms of the results include that it needs not only commitments but also clear directions for mitigation and adaptation and robust mechanisms put in place for the relevant parties to be held accountable to their commitments.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to critics, such issues could turn the conference into a "greenwashing" event of empty promises.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There is a criticism about the lack of people from most affected people and areas.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kaossara Sani became one of the persons who came from this place and sent her criticism by sending her manifesto to Forbes about what happened in Sahel and her criticism to COP26.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Academicians and practitioners on the field have floated several missing links of COP26 particularly the approach to climate change, disasters and public health consequences stemming from the meeting and how the neglect of healthcare will impact the Asia Pacific Region as a whole.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the Institute for Strategic Dialogue and a network of journalism organizations, the COP meeting became a target for climate misinformation, prominently "narratives of delay".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 9 November, Climate Action Tracker reported that the global human civilization is on track for a 2.7 °C temperature increase in the Earth system by the end of the century with current policies.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if the pledges for 2030 will be implemented, by 2.1 °C if the long-term targets will be implemented also and by 1.8 °C if in addition all the targets in discussion will be fully implemented.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Current targets for 2030 remain "totally inadequate".
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Coal and natural gas consumption are the main cause for the gap between pledges and policies.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 10 November, it was reported that the United States and China agreed on a framework to reduce carbon emissions by cooperating on measures to lower the use of methane, phase out the use of coal and increased protection of forests.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The request was criticized as illogical and self-defeating as it would end up harming people in developing countries the most and an article in the *Daily Beast* described the request as an attempt by China to sabotage the draft commitment.
[src:deforestation/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China was responsible for around 27% of the world's current GHG emissions in 2019.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Advertising mail includes advertising circulars, plastic mailers, coupon envelopes (Money Mailer, Valpak), catalogs, CDs, "pre-approved" credit card applications, and other commercial merchandising materials delivered to homes and businesses.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] It may be addressed to pre-selected individuals, or unaddressed and delivered on a neighbourhood-by-neighbourhood basis.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] North Carolina state historians say Lunsford Richardson "is widely to considered to have invented ‘junk mail.’" In the process of expanding the market for his new products made by the Vicks company of Greensboro, North Carolina.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Postal Service began allowing mail to be sent to rural addresses without including the name of the addressee.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Vicks sent out millions of samples of Vicks VapoRub.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Postal systems offer lower rates for buyers of bulk mail permits.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In order to qualify for these rates, marketers must format and sort the mail in specific ways – which reduces the handling required by the postal service.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Income from advertising mail represents a significant and growing portion of some postal services' budgets, and it is a service actively marketed by them.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In the United States, ad mail dollars decreased from $96.6 billion in 2004, to $80.9 billion in 2013.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] A study by Boston Consulting Group predicts that overall share of ad-spend in the US will increase from 11% in to 12% by 2020.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In Canada, addressed and unaddressed advertising mail accounted for 20% of Canada Post's revenue in 2005, and the share is increasing.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Postal services employ the terms *advertising mail*, *admail*, and *direct mail*, while avoiding and objecting to the pejorative term *junk mail*.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The United States Postal Service offers a direct mail service known as Every Door Direct Mail, that provides resources allowing businesses to target, design, print and mail to specific households without needing to know the addresses.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In many developed countries, advertising mail represents a significant and growing amount of the total volume of mail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In the United States, "Standard mail: advertising" comprised 29% of all mail in 1980 and 43% in 2003.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Direct mail is a common form of direct marketing, and may be employed by for-profit businesses, charities and other non-profits, political campaigns, and other organizations.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Direct mail encompasses a wide variety of marketing materials, including brochures, catalogs, postcards, newsletters and sales letters.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In 2015 more than 150 million direct mail promotions were sent out with a reported 42% of respondents scanning or reading the mail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Scammers also use direct mail in the form of auto warranty and home warranty scams.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Copywriters write the words, also known as copy, for direct mail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] These copywriters are known inside the trade as direct response copywriters.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Direct response copy follows a proven format based on testing results.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Graphic designers who specialize in direct marketing also play a key role in the success of direct mail programs.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Many direct mail marketers will mail different version of copy (A/B testing) to test the effectiveness of different appeals.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The winning mail package will be known as the control and the direct mail company will continue to mail the control until a different package produces improved results, usually measured by metrics such as revenue and conversion rate.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Some campaigns incorporate tactile embellishments—such as foil stamping, embossing, specialty UV coatings, metallic finishes, and soft-touch laminates—to attract attention and encourage interaction.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Advertisers often refine direct mail practices into targeted mailing in which mail is sent following database analysis to select recipients considered most likely to respond positively.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] This reduces costs for mailers by narrowing the mailing universe to only the most likely audience.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] For example, a person who has demonstrated an interest in golf may receive direct mail for golf-related products or perhaps for goods and services that are appropriate for golfers.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] This use of database analysis is a type of database marketing.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Alternatively, unaddressed direct mail may be sent on a neighbourhood-by-neighbourhood basis.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Whether at the individual or neighbourhood level, direct mail marketing allows recipients to be targeted, attempting to match the demographic profile of the recipients to one most closely matching that of likely customers.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Individually targeted direct mail may be tailored based on previous transactions and gathered data.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] For example, all male recipients of an offer may receive a personalized package with a man's picture on the cover while all female recipients receive a picture of a woman.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Often advertisers will include a Johnson Box in letters.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] These are aimed at drawing the targeted consumers into reading further in the letter.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] To the non-professional, direct mail may seem wasteful, yet the medium can be one of the most cost-effective.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Database targeting combined with an effective pricing, creative and list strategy can reduce waste and maximize profitable results for the mailer.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Testing is accomplished in a variety of ways including A/B split testing of new mailings versus a control and testing lists through "Nth" name selects.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Political campaigns make frequent use of direct mail, both to gain votes from the electorate as a whole, and to target certain groups of voters thought to be open to a candidate's message and to appeal for campaign funds.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Certain organizations and individuals have become known for their prowess in direct mail, including in the US, the Free Congress Foundation in the 1970s, Response Dynamics, Inc. in the 1980s, the National Congressional Club, and Richard Viguerie.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] With the advent of the Internet in political campaigns, direct mail became just one of many campaign management tools, but still played a significant role.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Nonprofit companies use direct mail marketing as a consistent form of advertising.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In its modern form, direct mail fundraising appeared in the United States after World War II when nationwide charities such as the National Easter Seal Society sought ways to broaden their fundraising base.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] It was only with the advent in the 1960s of the ZIP code and, later, the computer that direct mail fundraising began to gain wide use.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Before the ZIP code, it was difficult to target appropriate recipients of direct mail fundraising appeals, and before the computer, compiling and maintaining lists of supporters was tedious and costly.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] During the 1970s, when computers became increasingly affordable, the use of direct mail fundraising spread widely.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] It quickly became the means by which most Americans learned about and first provided financial support for their charities of choice.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The explosive growth of the nonprofit sector in the United States—quadrupling in the 1980s and doubling again in the 1990s and early 2000s—led to a massive expansion in the use of direct mail to build and sustain large, nationwide donor and membership lists.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In recent years, electronic communication media has been used more commonly among nonprofits.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Online, email, and social media campaigns, collectively referred to as digital fundraising, have been used in coordination with direct mail fundraising.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Nonprofits supplement direct mail campaigns with email blasts and social media posts, using similar messaging and visuals to tie the various communications together.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] However, digital fundraising has not grown fast enough to replace direct mail for most nonprofits.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In 2012, digital fundraising accounted for 7 percent of charitable donations in the United States.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] This form of marketing is increasingly used by charitable groups in the UK.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In 2013, £239 million was spent by British charities on direct mail advertising campaigns.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Direct mail marketing is under scrutiny by many of its former and current advocates.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The arguments against using direct mail marketing include possible impact on the environment and changing attitudes among consumers.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In the United States, the common practice of address standardization can defeat the purpose of advertising mail by stripping away local identity, thus leaving many recipients alienated.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] It is also argued that direct mail is not cost-efficient.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] It has been suggested that social media will eventually replace direct mail as the preferred method for marketing communications.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Those who believe direct mail marketing has a future cite its strong growth in 2011.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] It has been reported that large publishers like the Tribune Company and RR Donnelley have growing direct mail divisions.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Nonprofit organizations continue to use direct mail at a subsidized USPS rate.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] When targeted to other businesses rather than individuals, direct mail is known as a business-to-business mailing.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Traditionally, this worked in one of two ways: as a direct sale, therefore precluding the use of a salesperson or a retail store, or as a method of generating leads for a salesforce.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The former method was ideally used by products that were easy to sell, were familiar to the prospect and needed no demonstration.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The latter method was used for large-ticket items or for those that needed demonstration, for example.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] One method of direct mailing used in B2B is known as "bill-me." In this direct-mail marketing offer, the buyer is shipped the product prior to payment and is then sent an invoice later.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Several organizations offer opt-out services to people who wish to reduce or eliminate the amount of addressed advertising mail they receive.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In the UK, the Mailing Preference Service allows people to register with them for removal from posted as opposed to hand-delivered mail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] As of 2017 in the United States two organizations offering these services include Catalog Choice and DMAChoice.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] A similar organization by the name of 41pounds.org received customer complaints and then became defunct.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Another one by the name of Tonic Mailstopper (formerly GreenDimes) no longer appears to be in business either.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Several websites critical of junk mail have guides for people interested in reducing the amount of junk mail they get, such as the Center for a New American Dream.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In response to a US Supreme Court ruling (*Rowan v.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] 728 (1970)), the United States Postal Service enables an applicant to obtain a Prohibitory Order, which gives people the power to stop non-governmental organizations from sending them mail, and to demand such organizations remove the consumers’ information from their mailing lists.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In Canada, the highly publicized Red Dot Campaign offers advice on reducing unaddressed advertising mail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The campaign focuses on advertising the Canada Post policy to respect "No Junkmail" signs, noting that this policy is not promoted by Canada Post itself.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The name "red dot" refers to an internal marker used by Canada Post to indicate which households do not wish to receive unaddressed admail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The UK Royal Mail also offers an opt-out service, though unaddressed government mailings cannot be separated from advertisements, and those who opted out of the latter would stop receiving the former as well.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Several environmental groups express concern about the environmental impact generated by direct mail.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In the US, the Environmental Protection Agency estimates that 44% of junk mail is discarded without being opened or read, equalling four million tons of waste paper per year, with 32% recovered for recycling.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Further, the Ohio Office of Compliance Assistance and Pollution Prevention (OCAPP) estimates that 250,000 homes could be heated for a single day's junk mail (70,000,000,000,000/3 btus of energy or 28,870,000,000/21 kWh of energy).
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] In the UK, the Minister of State responsible for the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs estimated that "direct mail and promotions" accounted for between 500,000 and 600,000 tonnes of paper in 2002, with 13% being recycled.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The government and the Direct Marketing Association (UK) together agreed on recycling targets for the direct mail industry, including a goal of 55% by 2009, though the DMA's latest estimates are that the industry will fall well short of this mark.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Mike Berners-Lee estimates that receiving five letters per day plus two printed catalogs per week results in 480 kilograms (1,060 lb) CO2e per year.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] A *New York Times* article from 2009 states that in the United States 51.5 million metric tons of greenhouse gases are emitted each year from mail advertisements.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] The Environmental Protection Agency indicates that in 2009 total US greenhouse gas emissions were 6,700.10 million metric tons.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Recipients may conceive of advertising mail as a privacy problem, both because its generation requires extensive collection and use of information, and because receipt of mail can be an intrusion into the home.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Researchers at the University of California recently found that four out of five Americans favor a do-not-mail law, similar to the existing do-not-call telemarketing registry.
[src:deforestation/advertising-mail] Advertising mail has been criticized as a form of attention theft.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:deforestation/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:deforestation/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:deforestation/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:deforestation/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:deforestation/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange was produced in the United States beginning in the late 1940s and was used in industrial agriculture, and was also sprayed along railroads and power lines to control undergrowth in forests.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Nine chemical companies produced it, including Dow Chemical Company and Monsanto Company.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange exposure is linked to increased rates of birth defects, malignancies, cardiovascular diseases, and diabetes.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] The science on the causality between exposure and health problems remains incomplete.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. government has documented cases of leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma, and various kinds of cancer in exposed U.S. veterans, but not concluded a causal relationship or a plausible biological carcinogenic mechanism.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention identified an increase in the rate of birth defects of the children of exposed U.S. veterans.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] The impact of Agent Orange in Vietnam includes health and ecological effects.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] The government of Vietnam defined victims of Agent Orange by looking at where they live, their family history, and if the health problems have been linked to Agent Orange.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. government has described these figures as unreliable.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange has also caused enormous environmental damage in Vietnam.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] This has been described by numerous lawyers, historians and other academics as ecocide.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Defoliants eroded tree cover and seedling forest stock, making reforestation difficult in numerous areas.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] Animal species diversity is sharply reduced in contrast with unsprayed areas.
[src:deforestation/agent-orange-p01] The use of Agent Orange in Vietnam resulted in numerous legal actions.
